#Consecrate	SCHOOL:Evocation	DESCRIPTOR:Good	CLASSES:ALL=2	COMPS:V, S, M	CASTTIME:One standard action	RANGE:Close	TARGETAREA:20 foot radius emanation	DURATION:Two hours per level	SAVEINFO:None	SPELLRES:No	DESC:See Text
#Consecrate.MOD	DESC:Consecrate infuses the area with positive energy. Turn undead checks made there gain a +3 sacred bonus. Undead and Outsiders with the Evil subtype within the area suffer a –1 penalty on attack rolls, damage rolls, and saves. Undead cannot be created within or summoned into a Consecrated area. If the area contains a permanent fixture dedicated to your patron deity, pantheon, or good-aligned higher power, the effects are doubled (+6 sacred bonus on turning checks, –2 penalties for undead in the area). You cannot consecrate an area containing a fixture dedicated to another power, but any attempt to do so cuts off its connection with that power.

#Desecrate	SCHOOL:Evocation	DESCRIPTOR:Evil	CLASSES:ALL=2	COMPS:V, S, M	CASTTIME:One standard action	RANGE:Close	TARGETAREA:20 foot radius emanation	DURATION:Two hours per level	SAVEINFO:None	SPELLRES:No	DESC:See Text
#Desecrate.MOD	DESC:Desecrate infuses an area with unholy energy. Turn Undead checks within it take a -3 profane penalty and undead within it gain a +1 profane bonus on attack rolls, damage rolls, and saving throws. An undead creature created within or summoned into such an area gains +1 hit points per HD. Outsiders with the good subtype in a Desecrated area suffer a -1 penalty to attack rolls, damage rolls, and saves. If the Desecrated area contains an altar, shrine, or other permanent fixture dedicated to your deity or evilaligned higher power, the effect is doubled and anyone who casts Animate Dead within this area may create twice as many as usual.
#The effect is otherwise similar to Consecrate.

#The Armor of Darkness version is identical, but requires dedication to evil and works on undead.

#Hallow / Unhallow	SCHOOL:Evocation	DESCRIPTOR:Good|Evil	CLASSES:ALL=5	COMPS:V, S, DF	CASTTIME:Twenty-four hours	RANGE:Touch	TARGETAREA:Forty ft. radius emanating from the touched point	DURATION:Instantaneous	SAVEINFO:See text	SPELLRES:See text	DESC:See Text	DESC:Hallow and Unhallow make a site holy or unholy, thus warding it with a Magic Circle Against Evil (or Good) effect. Turn Undead checks gain a +4 sacred bonus (or -4 profane penalty), while Command Undead checks take a –4 sacred penalty (or get a +4 profane bonus).Spell resistance does not apply to this effect. Bodies interred in a Hallowed site cannot be turned into undead, but Undead created in an Unhallowed area gain +3 hit points per die. In either case the caster may fix a single spell effect to the site (which spells are eligible is up to the GM). Such spells last for a year and function throughout the site, regardless of the normal duration and area of effect. You may designate whether the effect applies to all creatures, creatures who share your faith or alignment, or creatures who adhere to another faith or alignment. At the end of the year, the chosen effect lapses, but it can be renewed or replaced simply by casting this spell once again. Saving throws and spell resistance apply to such secondary spells normally. An area can receive only one Hallow spell (and its associated spell effect) at a time. Hallow counters but does not dispel Unhallow. Material Component: Herbs, oils, and incense worth at least 1,000 GP, plus 1,000 GP per level of the spell to be included in the Hallowed area.


#Size Bonus
Enlarge/Reduce Person/Animal (Specify)
Transmutation
Level: 1
Components: V, S, M
Casting Time: One standard action
Range: Close (25 ft + 5 ft per 2 levels)
Target: One humanoid creature (Animal)
Duration: One minute per level (D)
Saving Throw: Fortitude negates
Spell Resistance: Yes
These spells alter the size of an appropriate
target creature by one size category. This affects
equipment, but the creature’s speed does not
change. Adjust damage from the target
creature’s melee attacks accordingly, but
projectile damage does not change save for
using the character’s new Strength since items
which leave the character’s possession return to
normal size. Magical properties, abilities, spells,
and items do not change. Opposing spells
designed to increase and decrease size cancel
each other fully or partially as appropriate and
only the strongest current spell of each type is
effective.
If insufficient room is available for size increases
the creature attains the maximum possible size and
may make a Strength check (using its increased
Strength) to burst any enclosures in the process. If it
fails, it is constrained without harm by the materials
enclosing it. The spell cannot crush a creature by
increasing its size.
Note that this spell does not correspond to the
SRD version of Enlarge or Reduce Person: it uses the
standard size chart rather than specified, and smaller,
bonuses. Game masters should play up the problems
of changing size or, if this effect remains overpowered
in their games, assign penalties for being clumsy at
this unnatural size.
Size of the Mote
Level: 2
Size of the Mote reduces the target creature by
two size categories. It is otherwise identical to Reduce
Person.
Giant’s Wrath
Level: 3
Giant’s Wrath enlarges the target creature by two
size categories and provides it with damage reduction
+3/- as a size bonus. It is otherwise identical to
Enlarge Person.






